                <p>in all 36 ways. The table shows that there are six ways in which <hi
                    rend="italic">i</hi> can be thrown, three ways in which 4 can be thrown. Hence
                    the odds are 6 to 3, or 2 to 1.</p>
                <p>But there is always an advantage in favour of the setter on the stake first
                    played for. The least disadvantageous main for the caster to call is 7.</p>
                <p>Take the case in which 7 is the main and £18 (to avoid fractions) the caster’s
                    stake, and £36 therefore the sum played for. Then (1) if 7 or 11 is thrown the
                    caster wins. There are eight ways out of 36 in his favour; therefore his
                    expectation on nicking is - <hi rend="subscript"> 3</hi> ⅞ths of £18 = £8. (2)
                    If the chance is 6, in order to win he must throw 6</p>
                <p>before he throws 7. There are five ways of throwing 6, and six ways of throwing
                    7. His expectation on 6 is therefore - <hi rend="subscript"> 5</hi><hi
                    rend="superscript"> δ</hi><hi rend="subscript"> 5</hi> ths of <hi
                    rend="subscript"> τ</hi><hi rend="superscript"> 5</hi><hi rend="subscript">
